    <title>Rubrics, Schedules, and Grades</title>
    <p> We will use a few rubrics for this course.  You will be given rubrics on class assignments, and 
      you will have access to all of the rubrics in Canvas. Here is the rubric for what is meant by Mastery.  
      For quiz and assessment outcomes in this class, your grade will be one of the following: M, P, R, N.
    </p>
      <table>
  <title>Mastery Rubric</title>
  <tabular halign="center" top="medium">
    <row bottom="medium">
      <cell right="medium">
        Grade
      </cell>
      <cell right="medium">
        Mastery Level
      </cell>
      <cell halign="left" right="medium">
        Description
      </cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="medium">
      <cell right="medium">
        M
      </cell>
      <cell right="medium">
        Mastered
      </cell>
      <cell halign="left" right="medium">
        The solution to the problem is structured, complete, and clear. Correct 
        methods are used, the solution is legible and easy to follow, complete steps 
        are provided, and mathematically, the reasoning is sound. The solution is 
        simplified with correct notation or units where appropriate. There are no 
        errors in the work submitted.
      </cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="medium">
      <cell right="medium">
        P
      </cell>
      <cell right="medium">
        Progressing
      </cell>
      <cell halign="left" right="medium">
        The solution shows growth in understanding the topic, but may be incomplete 
        or omit some steps. The work has correct components, but is not presented in 
        a coherent mathematical format. There are minimal errors that do not affect 
        the correctness of the answer in this situation.
      </cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="medium">
      <cell  right="medium">
        R
      </cell>
      <cell right="medium">
        Reassess
      </cell>
      <cell halign="left" right="medium">
        The solution shows a start to the process but may be incomplete, missing some steps. 
        The work has incorrect components and is not presented in a coherent mathematical 
        format. Some errors change the correctness of the process as it applies to the 
        situation. The presented work makes it unclear what is understood about the concept.
      </cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="medium">
      <cell right="medium">
        N
      </cell>
      <cell right="medium">
        Not able to asses
      </cell>
      <cell right="medium">
        There was no attempt made, or there is not enough fundamental work to provide feedback.
      </cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>
</table>
